🌿 ब्रह्मगीता – ऐन्दवोपाख्यानम् (सर्ग १७८)
भाग ८ : धारणा की अद्भुत शक्ति
Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178)
Part Eight: The Extraordinary Power of One-Pointed Contemplation
मूल श्लोक
तयोस्ते तनया दुःखकलिता विपिनं गताः।
कृतौर्ध्वदैहिकास्त्यक्त्वा व्यवहारं समाधये॥३२॥
धारणानां समस्तानां का स्यादुत्तमसिद्धिदा।
धारणा यन्मयाः सन्तः स्यामः सर्वेश्वरा वयम्॥३३॥
इति ते तत्र सञ्चिन्त्य बद्धपद्मासना दश।
इदं सञ्चिन्तयामासुर्निर्विघ्ने कन्दरोदरे॥३४॥
पद्मजाधिष्ठिताशेषजगद्धारणया स्थिताः।
भवाम पद्मजोपेतं जगद्रूपमविघ्नतः॥३५॥
इति सञ्चिन्त्य सब्रह्म जगद्धारणया चिरम्।
निमीलितदृशस्तस्थुस्ते चित्रलिखिता इव॥३६॥
अथैतद्धारणाबद्धचित्तास्ते तावदच्युताः।
आसन्मासान्दशाष्टौ च यावत्ते तत्र देहकाः॥३७॥
शुष्काः कङ्कालतां याताः क्रव्यादैश्चर्विताङ्गकाः।
नाशमभ्याययुस्तत्र छायाभागा इवातपैः॥३८॥

🌿 हिन्दी भावार्थ
अपने माता-पिता के वियोग से अत्यन्त दुःखी उन दसों भाइयों ने पहले उनके अन्त्येष्टि संस्कार सम्पन्न किये।
फिर उन्होंने संसार का परित्याग कर दिया।
वे वन की एक निर्जन गुफा में चले गये।
किन्तु उनका उद्देश्य केवल दुःख से भागना नहीं था।
वे सत्य की खोज करना चाहते थे।
उन्होंने विचार किया—
सभी धारणाओं में कौन-सी धारणा सर्वोच्च सिद्धि प्रदान करती है?
दीर्घ चिन्तन के बाद उन्होंने निश्चय किया—
यदि हम सम्पूर्ण ब्रह्माण्ड सहित ब्रह्मा का अखण्ड ध्यान करें,
तो उसी चेतना में एकरूप हो जायेंगे।
वे पद्मासन में बैठ गये।
नेत्र बन्द हो गये।
शरीर अचल हो गया।
समय बीतता गया।
अठारह मास तक उनकी धारणा तनिक भी विचलित नहीं हुई।
धीरे-धीरे उनके शरीर सूख गये।
हड्डियाँ रह गयीं।
वन्य पशुओं ने शरीर भक्षण कर लिया।
किन्तु ध्यान नहीं टूटा।
यहीं से वसिष्ठजी एक महान् रहस्य प्रकट करने वाले हैं।

🌿 English Reflection
The ten brothers first fulfilled their worldly duties by performing the final rites of their parents.
Then they renounced worldly life.
Seeking the highest Truth,
they retired to a solitary cave.
There they asked themselves a profound question:
Among all contemplations, which one leads to the highest realization?
They concluded:
"We shall meditate upon Brahmā together with the entire universe until no distinction remains."
Seated motionless in deep meditation,
they remained absorbed for eighteen months.
Their bodies withered.
Their flesh disappeared.
Even the animals of the forest consumed what remained.
Yet their contemplation never broke.
The body perished.
The meditation did not.
The story is quietly shifting our attention away from the physical form toward the enduring reality of Consciousness.

🌿 Vedantic Insight
This is not merely a story about intense meditation.
It is a profound declaration that Consciousness is not dependent upon the body.
The body belongs to time.
The mind becomes purified through contemplation.
But the Witness is ever-present.
The destruction of the body is not the destruction of Awareness.
The sage invites us to discover that what truly meditates is not the body, but Consciousness itself.

🌿 Practical Contemplation
Every day the body changes.
Thoughts change.
Emotions change.
Yet something within silently witnesses every change.
Spend a few moments each day abiding as that Witness.
Steady contemplation gradually loosens the mistaken identity with the body and reveals the peace that has always been present.

🌸 Living Vedanta Library Conclusion
The ten brothers teach us that the highest meditation is not an escape from life.
It is the unwavering recognition of the Reality that underlies life itself.
Bodies may arise and pass away.
Time may consume all forms.
But Pure Consciousness neither withers nor dies.
It silently illumines every appearance.
The story has now reached its turning point.
In the next verses, Maharshi Vasiṣṭha will reveal one of the most astonishing truths in Advaita:
Their meditation did not merely transform themselves—it became entire universes.
